## Memory Leak Analysis: `ScrollTracker`

There are **three distinct problems** in this component — two are the primary leak sources, and one is a subtle logical bug that compounds the first two.

---

## Problem 1: Missing Dependency Array (Re-registers on Every Render)

```jsx
// ❌ No second argument — runs after EVERY render
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', ...);
    window.addEventListener('resize', ...);
});
```

When `useEffect` has no dependency array, React runs it **after every single render** — not just on mount. This creates a self-reinforcing cycle:

```
Component renders
  → useEffect runs → adds scroll + resize listeners
    → User scrolls → handler fires
      → setState called → component re-renders
        → useEffect runs again → adds MORE listeners
          → User scrolls → now 2 handlers fire → 2 setState calls
            → re-renders twice → adds 2 MORE listeners
              → ... grows without bound
```

Each navigation away and back **resets** the component but the listeners already attached to `window` survive. On the next mount, the cycle starts fresh and adds on top of whatever already accumulated.

---

## Problem 2: No Cleanup Function (Listeners Never Removed)

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
    // ❌ No return () => { removeEventListener(...) }
});
```

`useEffect` supports an optional **cleanup function** returned from the callback. React calls this cleanup:
- Before re-running the effect (on the next render, if no deps array or deps changed)
- When the component **unmounts**

Without it, every listener ever registered on `window` lives forever — even after the component that registered it is long gone. The `window` object is global and persists for the entire page lifetime. These orphaned handlers hold **closure references** to old React fiber state, preventing garbage collection of the entire component subtree.

---

## Problem 3: Anonymous Functions Can't Be Removed

```jsx
// ❌ New function object created on every useEffect call
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
```

`removeEventListener` works by matching the **exact same function reference** that was passed to `addEventListener`. Two arrow functions with identical bodies are two completely different objects in memory:

```js
const a = () => {};
const b = () => {};
a === b; // false — different objects, different references
```

Since a new anonymous function is created on every `useEffect` invocation, you have **no reference** to give `removeEventListener`. Even if you added a cleanup `return`, this would silently do nothing:

```jsx
// ❌ This cleanup does nothing — it creates yet another new function
return () => {
    window.removeEventListener('scroll', () => { ... }); // different reference!
};
```

The fix is to declare named handler variables **inside the effect** so the cleanup closure can reference the same objects that were registered.

---

## Bonus Problem: Stale Closure on `lastScrollY`

```jsx
const [lastScrollY, setLastScrollY] = useState(0);

useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
        // ❌ `lastScrollY` is captured from the closure at effect-creation time
        // It's always 0 (or whatever it was when this effect last ran)
        setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollY ? 'down' : 'up');
        setLastScrollY(currentScrollY);
    });
});
```

The scroll handler closes over the `lastScrollY` **value** at the time the effect ran. Since state updates are asynchronous and the effect ran before the re-render reflected the new value, the direction comparison reads stale data. The fix is to use a `ref` for tracking the previous scroll position — refs are mutable containers that always reflect the current value without triggering re-renders or causing closure staleness.

---

## React 18 Strict Mode Makes This Immediately Visible

In development, React 18 Strict Mode intentionally **double-invokes effects**:

```
Mount  → effect runs (adds 2 listeners)
Unmount → cleanup runs (but there is no cleanup → listeners stay)
Remount → effect runs again (adds 2 MORE listeners)
```

So in development you start with **4 listeners** instead of 2, and the bug becomes obvious immediately — scroll events fire multiple times, direction flips erratically, and console logs duplicate. This is by design: Strict Mode acts as an early-warning system for exactly this class of bug.

---

## Corrected Component

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

function ScrollTracker() {
    const [scrollY, setScrollY] = useState(0);
    const [scrollDirection, setScrollDirection] = useState('none');

    // ✅ Use a ref instead of state for the "previous scroll position" tracker.
    //    Refs are always current (no stale closure), and updating them doesn't
    //    trigger a re-render — they're perfect for values you need to read inside
    //    event handlers but don't need to display.
    const lastScrollYRef = useRef(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        // ✅ Named handler functions declared inside the effect so the cleanup
        //    closure can reference the exact same function objects.
        const handleScroll = () => {
            const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;

            // ✅ Read from ref — always the current value, never stale
            setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollYRef.current ? 'down' : 'up');

            // ✅ Update ref synchronously (no re-render, no stale closure)
            lastScrollYRef.current = currentScrollY;

            setScrollY(currentScrollY);
        };

        const handleResize = () => {
            console.log('Window resized, recalculating...');
            setScrollY(window.scrollY);
        };

        // ✅ Register listeners
        window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
        window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

        // ✅ Return a cleanup function that removes the exact same references.
        //    Called on unmount AND before re-running the effect (not applicable
        //    here since we have an empty dep array, but good practice).
        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
            window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
        };
    }, []); // ✅ Empty array: run ONLY on mount, clean up ONLY on unmount.
            //    Safe because handlers read from refs (not stale state).

    return (
        <div style={{ position: 'fixed', top: 10, right: 10, padding: '10px', background: '#333', color: '#fff' }}>
            <p>Scroll Y: {scrollY}</p>
            <p>Direction: {scrollDirection}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default ScrollTracker;
```

---

## Summary Table

| Problem | Root Cause | Effect | Fix |
|---|---|---|---|
| No dependency array | `useEffect` runs every render | Listener count grows exponentially per scroll/resize event | Add `[]` as second argument |
| No cleanup function | Listeners persist after unmount | Orphaned handlers accumulate across navigation cycles; old component state kept alive | Return `() => removeEventListener(...)` |
| Anonymous functions | New object reference each call | `removeEventListener` silently fails to match | Declare named `const handler = () => {}` inside effect |
| `lastScrollY` as state | Stale closure captures old value | Direction detection reads wrong previous position | Replace with `useRef` |

The core mental model: **every `addEventListener` must have a matching `removeEventListener` with the same function reference**, and `useEffect`'s cleanup return is the designed mechanism for this in React's component lifecycle.

